🔑 The One Technical Insight That Changes Everything
After 10 years, here's what separates truly great AI engineers from average ones:
They obsess over evaluation.
Anyone can call an API and get a response. The engineers I've promoted are the ones who ask: "But how do we know it's working well? How do we measure degradation? How do we know fine-tuning helped?"
Before you ship any AI feature, define:
python# What does "good" look like?
metrics = {
    "faithfulness": "Does the answer come from the retrieved docs?",
    "relevance": "Does the retrieved context match the query?",
    "correctness": "Is the answer factually right?",
    "latency_p99": "Is it fast enough at the 99th percentile?",
    "cost_per_query": "Is this economically viable at scale?"
}
Put this thinking in your projects. Write about it on GitHub. Mention it in interviews.
That one habit will make you stand out from every other student — because almost none of them think about it.
You already have everything you need to start. Go build.
